rComments: Elle est très gentille et, disons, décontractée, mais ses cours peuvent être très longs, surtout lorsqu'elle décide de parler de choses n'ayant aucun rapport avec le cours. Si vous êtes chanceux, il y aura un chien dans le cours!

Très détaillée dans ce qu'elle recherche, les cours comme tels sont ennuyants mais je ne reccommanderais pas de ne pas s'y présenter. Très gentille et compréhensive, surtout car l'anglais est notre langue seconde.
She's is a kind person, but with such a small class it feels a lot like a DGD. The translation is usually given as homework if you don't finish it in class.
Sylvie encouraged participation, but could be quite rude and mocking if we answered something incorrectly. The class was difficult but she can teach you a lot if you listen.

So rude! She will make you feel so stupid for participating. I don't even know what I was supposed to learn in this class. How are we supposed to be good at translating (which is what she expects) when this is the first time anyone in the class has done this. Awful. 0/10

She was really tough to her students. Do not take this class if french is your first language! She will question your capability to be in the class. If you make little mistakes, she will question your intelligence. If you don't perfect the material she gave you the first week, she will call you out on it.

This prof was great! I liked that the vibe of her class was very chill and that you could participate without being criticized. She has quite the sassy personality which makes the class enjoyable. The texts translated in class were a little repetitive but very easy. You don't have to study much for the midterm/final either since they are open book.

Whoever said that she was a tough grader must be extremely dumb lol. Her tests are SO easy and pretty much everyone gets an A+. Never any surprises, everything is always clear. She is awesome, and so nice! I love her so much!

She wants something very specific, but can't convey it to others, so her students end up confused and then she gets angry at them. Asking questions in class will often get you ridiculed and she will blatantly contradict herself from class to class. I wouldn't call it a hard class, but she's just not clear enough to make it an easy one.

She knows her stuff but does a poor job of conveying her knowledge. She is unorganized with her ideas and seems to change her mind about rules. She can be quite rude and tear what you think is right apart. There is no guideline to help you, you have to intuitively know how to translate or you won't do well. Don't try to argue with her it's hopeless

She's quite sassy. It's possible to learn from her and improve throughout the semester, though you have to put a lot of effort into it. She does often give extra assignments at the end of the semester to help students improve their grades.
Sassy, hilarious. Hard grader, but your grade does improve throughout the semester.

Excellent introductory course. More than once, she has stayed behind after class to help students understand. She gives very clear examples and does lots of hands-on practice in class. She points out "bloopers" made on students' papers (without naming them) and says why they were wrong, which might offend. My life-saver this semester.

Hard marker and sometimes brings personal stuff into lectures, but as a student with severe health issues causing me to miss many classes, she was extremely kind and accomodating. She gives a lot of helpful, real world experiences too.
whoever said she has no qualifications is wrong. She's certified in french-english-spanish translation by the ATIO (Association of Translators and Interpreters of Ontario)

Look, she talks a lot about her personal life but deep inside she is an AMAZING person. I was struggling a lot in her class but I spoke to her and she really did a lot for me to pass her class. Despite what you hear, she is awesome. She may seem weird and talkative, but she is a very wonderful person. I am honoured to have had her as a prof.

Tough marker, but I feel like I learned a ton in this class and enjoyed it a lot. Very nice lady, makes lots of jokes. Criticism can sometimes seem harsh but she is just trying to make it clear why something is a mistake.. overall feel better off for having been in this class.
Tough marker. Sometimes doesn't really know how to explain stuff ("just because!") and the pace of the class can be really slow. She's very nice though.
Excellent professor. Really nice, pleasant and helpful.

She presents herself as funny and friendly in class. However, don't bother speak to her about getting some marks back. She has made up her mind. She has that attitude that because she's been teaching at Ottawa University for so long that she can say and do whatever she feels like. SHe is extremely picky on word choice, and is very verbally abusive
Very nice lady. Extremely tough marker. I didn't find she made fun of anyone, simply compared difficulties between francophones and anglophones.

She jokes around a lot and can hurt your feelings; however, try not to take it personally. Find a friend who's taken the class before--she often uses the same texts (coffee, medicine, POPULATION). Don't argue with her unless you really want to...it's mostly useless and can leave you feeling pretty low. And get ready for her real life stories...
Has a background in Psychology and has no business teaching in this department. Unqualified.

There is no room for your opinion in her classes. She is right and you are wrong; it is that simple. Trying to challenge this will result in her becoming either defensive or snippy with you. Her "personal preferences" for one word over another are completely artibrary and will probably lose you marks. If this is your elective for Spanish, drop it.
She is friendly and funny during class, but is rude and judgmental when you speak to her one on one.
she does nor have a complete control of the languages.

Excellent prof! I don't see why everyone's complaining. She taught things that books and other profs don't have, and that was practical problem-solving strategies. I thought she had a great sense of humor and, for the record, she doesn't make fun of francophones/anglophones, just points out what each one will typically find more challinging.

According to her, everyone else is wrong (and she is right).  Low grades are common in her class, and when confronting her about them, nothing is gained.  She makes fun of her francophone class in her anglophone class, and vice-versa.  If you have a friend in the ``flip`` class, you can prove that she backstabs both classes.  Awful teacher, beware!
TRANSLATION- VERY HELPFULL, ALWAYS SMILLING/GREAT SENSE OF HUMOUR, KEEPS CLASS INTERESTED, OBVIOUSLY LOVES WHAT SHE DOES

Avoid taking her class unless you absolutely have to. She'll make you feel likea  bag of cold crap every day. Unless you can stand being called stupid repeatedly in front of the entire class, run away and don't look back.
Verbally abusive. Often refuses to reconsider or explain grades. Makes inappropriate comments about individual student performance in front of the class. Frequent mood swings.
Extremely verbally abusive
Real nice lady. She'll teach you useful stuff, but don't screw around: do the work and don't talk too much. Uses impossible to translate material. Extremely hard marker.
